%N A387129 Second numbers B = a(n) of two numbers (A, B) such that the sums 2*A^2 + B^2 = p == 3 mod 8, where p = A007520(n) and A = A387128(n).
%C A387129 Prime numbers p congruent to 3 mod 8 can be written as the sum of twice the square of an integer A and of the square of another integer B, i.e., 2*A^2 + B^2 = p, where A = A387128(n), B = a(n) (this sequence), and p = A007520(n) == 3 mod 8.
%C A387129 This representation is unique, i.e., for a given n, there are no other integer values of A(n) and B(n) such that p(n) = 2 * A(n)^2 + B(n)^2 where p(n) = A007520(n), the 3 mod 8 prime numbers.
%C A387129 For all n, A = A387128(n) and B = a(n) are always odd.
%C A387129 Terms are ordered according to increasing order of A007520(n).
